  1. Create a missingness indicator for the variables gen, phb and `tv.
boys_missingness <- boys %>%
  mutate(gen_missingness = is.na(gen),
         phb_missingness = is.na(phb),
         tv_missingness  = is.na(tv))
  1. Assess whether missingness in the variables gen, phb and tv is related to someones age.
boys_missingness %>% 
  group_by(gen_missingness) %>% 
  summarise(age = mean(age))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   gen_missingness   age
##   <lgl>           <dbl>
## 1 FALSE           14.0 
## 2 TRUE             6.79
boys_missingness %>% 
  group_by(phb_missingness) %>% 
  summarise(age = mean(age))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   phb_missingness   age
##   <lgl>           <dbl>
## 1 FALSE           14.0 
## 2 TRUE             6.79
boys_missingness %>% 
  group_by(tv_missingness) %>% 
  summarise(age = mean(age))
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   tv_missingness   age
##   <lgl>          <dbl>
## 1 FALSE          14.1 
## 2 TRUE            7.02

The mean age for all of the for both FALSE and TRUE is very similar, so age does seem to have a correlation with the missing data.

9. Create a density plot of age, splitting the densities by gen using the fill aesthetic.

boys %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, fill = gen)) +
  geom_density() +
  theme_minimal()

10. Create a diverging bar chart for hgt in the boys data set, that displays for every age year that years mean height in deviations from the overall average hgt.

boys %>% 
  select(age, hgt) %>% 
  drop_na() %>% 
  mutate(age = as.factor(age), hgt_dev = hgt - mean(hgt, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  group_by(age) %>% 
  summarise(hgt_dev = mean(hgt_dev, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(hgt_dev, age)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  theme_minimal()

Regression visualization

  1. Load the data elastic1 and elastic2 and bind the data frames together using the function bind_rows() and add a grouping variable indicating whether an observation comes from elastic1 or from elastic2.
library(DAAG)

help(elastic1)
## starting httpd help server ... done
help(elastic2)

elastics <-
  bind_rows("elastic1" = elastic1, "elastic2" = elastic2, .id = "set")
  1. Create a scatterplot mapping stretch on the x-axis and distance on the y-axis, and map the just created group indicator as the color aesthetic.
elastics %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = stretch, y = distance, color = set)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme_minimal()

  1. Recreate the previous plot, but now assess whether the results of the two data sets appear consistent by adding a linear regression line.
elastics %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = stretch, y = distance, color = set)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

  1. For each of the data sets elastic1 and elastic2, fit a regression model with y = distance on x = stretch using lm(y ~ x, data).
fit1 <- lm(distance ~ stretch, elastic1)
fit2 <- lm(distance ~ stretch, elastic2)
  1. For both of the previously created fitted models, determine the fitted values and the standard errors of the fitted values, and the proportion explained variance R2.
fit1 %>%
  predict(se.fit = TRUE)

  1. Study the residual versus leverage plots for both models.
fit1 %>% plot(which = 5)

fit2 %>% plot(which = 5)

  1. **Use the elastic2 variable stretch to obtain predictions on the model fitted on elastic1.*
pred <- predict(fit1, newdata = elastic2)
  1. Now make a scatterplot to investigate similarity between the predicted values and the observed values for elastic2.
pred <- data.frame(distance = pred, stretch  = elastic2$stretch)

ggplot() +
  geom_point(data = elastic2, mapping = aes(x = stretch, y = distance), color = "Green") +
  geom_line(data = elastic2, mapping = aes(x = stretch, y = distance), color = "Green") +
  geom_point(data = pred, mapping = aes(x = stretch, y = distance), color = "Red") +
  geom_line(data = pred, mapping = aes(x = stretch, y = distance), color = "Red") +
  theme_minimal()
